[normal]Will the Government
[normal]’s current approach towards low-
[normal]carbon inn
[normal]ovation help to achieve the UK’s legally
[normal]-
[normal]binding targets at the lowest 
[normal]possible cost?
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Does the Government have the right balance of focus between energy efficiency, renewable energy and other low carbon technologies?
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]What outcomes, if any, 
[normal]is
[normal] the
[normal] Low-
[normal]Carbon Innovation Coordination Group
[normal] 
[normal](
[normal]LCICG
[normal])
[normal] likely to achieve? How should its forthcoming strategy drive more investment into low
[normal]-
[normal]carbon innovation, and how should it measure su
[normal]ccess?
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]How should 
[normal]the Department for Energy and Climate Change (
[normal]DECC
[normal])
[normal] ensure t
[normal]hat its remai
[normal]ning capital allocation for low-
[normal]carbon innovation will be spent wisely, after two years of 
[normal]underspend
[normal]?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.1
[normal] 
[normal]UK p
[normal]ublic funding for 
[normal]low-carbon 
[normal]innovation 
[normal]has reduced annually since the G
[normal]overnment spending review in 2010
[normal] (National Audit Office, 2013)
[normal]. 
[normal]Research by the Grantham Research Institute on Climate Change and the Environment suggests that the 
[normal]current 
[normal]level of 
[normal]public funding for low-carbon innovation, and 
[normal]the way in which it is targeted
[normal], 
[normal]is insufficient
[normal] to achieve the UK’s legally
[normal]-
[normal]binding 
[normal]2050 emissions reduction targets
[normal] at the lowest possible cost.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The l[bold]evel[bold] of support for low-carbon innovatio[bold]n in the UK[bold]2.2 
[normal]The
[normal] key 
[normal]finding
[normal] 
[normal]of 
[normal]a
[normal] recent 
[normal]research 
[normal]project
[normal] by the Grantham Research Institute
[normal] 
[normal](
[normal]Aghion
[normal] 
[normal]et al
[normal].
[normal], 2012) 
[normal]is that there is 
[normal]a 
[normal]strong path dependency
[normal] 
[normal]which determines
[normal] the direction of innovation
[normal]. B
[normal]usinesses
[normal] which have innovated in 
[normal]low-carbon
[normal] 
[normal]technologies
[normal] in the past, 
[normal]and 
[normal]which 
[normal]are exposed to 
[normal]more 
[normal]low-carbon
[normal] 
[normal]innovation in the economy, 
[normal]are more likely to direct their research activit
[normal]ies
[normal] to
[normal]wards
[normal] 
[normal]low-carbon
[normal] 
[normal]innovation in the future
[normal].
[normal] Similarly, 
[normal]businesses
[normal] 
[normal]with a history of 
[normal]‘
[normal]dirty
[normal]’
[normal] innovation, and 
[normal]which are 
[normal]located in economies 
[normal]that are 
[normal]more speciali
[normal]s
[normal]ed 
[normal]in
[normal] 
[normal]‘
[normal]dirty
[normal]’
[normal] innovation, are more likely to focus on 
[normal]it
[normal] in the future.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.3 
[normal]Since today
[normal]’s 
[normal]stock of 
[normal]‘
[normal]dirty
[normal]’
[normal] innovation is much greater than that of clean
[normal] innovation
[normal], the path dependency e
[normal]ff
[normal]ect tend
[normal]s
[normal] to 
[normal]lock economies into 
[normal]high-carbon research and 
[normal]high
[normal]-
[normal]carbon emissions technologies, even after the introduction of a mild carbon 
[normal]pricing mechanism
[normal] or 
[normal]research and development
[normal] subsidies for clean
[normal] innovation
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.4 
[normal]This highlights the desirability of acting 
[normal]early
[normal] 
[normal]to shift incentives 
[normal]away from 
[normal]‘
[normal]dirty
[normal]’
[normal] innovation and towards low-carbon innovation.
[normal] Indeed,
[normal] the longer the delay
[normal], the more 
[normal]difficult and 
[normal]expensive it becomes to redirect the economy 
[normal]towards clean technologies
[normal], as shown by 
[normal]Acemoglu
[normal] 
[normal]et al
[normal].
[normal] (2012)
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Curr
[normal]ent UK policies 
[normal]are not sufficient
[normal] to move innovation on to a low-carbon pathway and
[normal] this
[normal] 
[normal]will make
[normal] the UK dependent on foreign technology
[normal] 
[normal]to meet its 
[normal]2050 
[normal]emissions reduction 
[normal]target
[normal] at least cost
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.5 O
[normal]nce the economy has 
[normal]shifted to a low-carbon 
[normal]innovation pathway
[normal], 
[normal]the 
[normal]path dependency effect 
[normal]implies
[normal] that the economy then naturally lock
[normal]s
[normal] itself into 
[normal]low-carbon
[normal] 
[normal]technologies
[normal], removing the need for further
[normal] 
[normal]Government support
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]This further strengthens the case for early 
[normal]Government 
[normal]action to support 
[normal]low-carbon innovation
[normal],
[normal] which can be relaxed in the future as the economy’s stock of 
[normal]low-carbon 
[normal]knowledge
[normal] grows
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]However, c
[normal]lear 
[normal]criteria governing
[normal] 
[normal]future 
[normal]reduc
[normal]tion
[normal]s
[normal] in
[normal] 
[normal]Government support for 
[normal]innovation 
[normal]must be
[normal] set
[normal] in advance
[normal] to prevent unexpected policy
[normal] cha
[normal]nges
[normal] 
[normal]that
[normal] could inhibit investment. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The type of support provided for low-carbon innovation in the UK[bold]2.6 
[normal]T
[normal]he UK’s current strategy 
[normal]appears
[normal] 
[normal]to prioriti
[normal]s
[normal]e policies
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]such as
[normal] 
[normal]feed-in tariffs
[normal] 
[normal]and a carbon price floor
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]which promote deployment rather than
[normal] 
[normal]direct support 
[normal]for
[normal] 
[normal]research and development
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]However, 
[normal]as 
[normal]shown
[normal] by 
[normal]Acemoglu
[normal] 
[normal]et al
[normal]. (2012), 
[normal]environmental polic
[normal]ies
[normal] 
[normal]that are economically optimal 
[normal]to fight climate change not only
[normal] 
[normal]address demand
[normal] 
[normal]but also
[normal] 
[normal]directly incentivi
[normal]s
[normal]e the development of 
[normal]low-carbon 
[normal]technologies.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.7 Providing more direct support for research and development
[normal] 
[normal]for
[normal] low-carbon technologies
[normal], for example 
[normal]through
[normal] tax credits
[normal] and subsidies, would provide better value for money and could be economically advantageous for the UK as it is more likely to benefit 
[normal]UK 
[normal]businesses.
[normal] Indeed, 
[normal]as shown by 
[normal]Dechezleprêtre
[normal] 
[normal]&amp;
[normal] 
[normal]Glachant
[normal] (2013),
[normal] 
[normal]deployment policies 
[normal]incentivi
[normal]s
[normal]e innovation activities not 
[normal]just
[normal] 
[normal]in the UK
[normal] but also in 
[normal]other
[normal] countries
[normal]. While these deployment policies certainly have a positive impact on
[normal] global 
[normal]efforts to tackle 
[normal]climate change
[normal], they 
[normal]may provide less economic benefit to the UK and 
[normal]hence may
[normal] be less poli
[normal]tically acceptable.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.1 The best strategy for the UK G
[normal]overnment 
[normal]is to 
[normal]target its 
[normal]support for 
[normal]low-carbon innovation 
[normal]at technologies that have the highest 
[normal]potential
[normal] 
[normal]for 
[normal]emissions reduction
[normal]s
[normal], are 
[normal]furthest away from the market
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]and 
[normal]have the highest knowledge 
[normal]spillovers
[normal] (i
[normal].
[normal]e
[normal].
[normal] knowledge
[normal] benefits for other inventors).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.2 Research by the Grantham Research Institute
[normal] 
[normal](
[normal]Dechezle
[normal]prêtre
[normal] 
[normal]et al
[normal].
[normal], 2013) has shown that 
[normal]knowledge 
[normal]spillover
[normal] 
[normal]benefits 
[normal](
[normal]i.e.
[normal] the societal benefits that justify policy intervention) 
[normal]are much higher in radically new low
[normal]-
[normal]carbon technologies, such as renewable energy technologies, than in technologies 
[normal]aimed at improving the efficiency of existing 
[normal]high-
[normal]carbon tec
[normal]hnologies. This justifies prioriti
[normal]s
[normal]ing renewable energy technologies, in particular the most radically new 
[normal]technologies 
[normal](
[normal]for example
[normal] 
[normal]off
[normal]shore 
[normal]wind
[normal] and
[normal] marine energy), over energy efficiency techn
[normal]ologies
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4
[normal].
[normal]1 Th
[normal]e
[normal] measurement of success
[normal] is 
[normal]important to
[normal] sustain 
[normal]G
[normal]overnment support 
[normal]for
[normal] the LCICG
[normal]. 
[normal]R
[normal]esearchers at
[normal] 
[normal]the Grantham Research Institute have 
[normal]developed three
[normal] 
[normal]indicators that can be used
[normal] at the national level
[normal] to assess the success of 
[normal]low-carbon innovation
[normal] in the
[normal] UK:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Patent applications filed by UK businesses 
[normal]for
[normal] low-carbon technologies, both in the UK and elsewhere. 
[normal]One benefit
[normal] of 
[normal]using 
[normal]patent applications 
[normal]as a metric is that they allow the identification of
[normal] low-carbon technologies 
[normal]at a highly disaggregated leve
[normal]l
[normal] (
[normal]e.g.
[normal] wave energy patents)
[normal] and 
[normal]of their link to
[normal] UK-based applicants
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Exports of low-ca
[normal]rbon capital goods from the UK (
[normal]e,g
[normal],
[normal] wind turbines
[normal])
[normal]. 
[normal]So far w
[normal]e have identified about 20 different low-carbon capital goods that we are able to trace in international t
[normal]rade databases
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Foreign investments in UK-based low-carbon 
[normal]businesses and, conversely, 
[normal]investments 
[normal]made by
[normal] 
[normal]UK-based low-carbon 
[normal]businesses 
[normal]in
[normal] foreign countries, are 
[normal]another
[normal] 
[normal]good indicator 
[normal]of
[normal] 
[normal]the success 
[normal]of
[normal] any low-carbon innovation strategy
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.2 
[normal]Two of these indicators seem already 
[normal]to be 
[normal]part of the metrics
[normal] used by the LCICG
[normal]. We 
[normal]recommend that 
[normal]the 
[normal]international 
[normal]investment indicator should be added.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.3 
[normal]Ideally
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]the
[normal] LCICG 
[normal]sh
[normal]ould try to measure not only the impact of low-carbon innovation policies 
[normal]on the growth of the low-carbon sector
[normal], but also the impact of these policies on the growth of the economy as a whole. A key result from 
[normal]recent research by the Grantham Research Institute 
[normal]is that a redirection of innovation from 
[normal]‘
[normal]dirty
[normal]’
[normal] to 
[normal]low-carbon 
[normal]techn
[normal]ologies can lead to higher economic growth in the medium
[normal] term
[normal] because 
[normal]low-carbon 
[normal]technologies generate much larger knowledge spillovers in the economy than the 
[normal]‘
[normal]dirty
[normal]’
[normal] technologie
[normal]s they replace (
[normal]Dechezleprêtre
[normal] 
[normal]et al
[normal].
[normal], 2013). A necessary condition for 
[normal]low-c
[normal]arbon 
[normal]policies 
[normal]to 
[normal]impact
[normal] 
[normal]growth of
[normal] the economy 
[normal]more broadly 
[normal]is that
[normal] 
[normal]the 
[normal]technologies
[normal] they support
[normal] 
[normal]must 
[normal]generate
[normal] 
[normal]benefits
[normal] outside their 
[normal]own fields
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.4 
[normal]For 
[normal]example
[normal], 
[normal]Dechezleprêtre
[normal] 
[normal]et al
[normal].
[normal] (2013) found that clean patents in the car industry relating to the 
[normal]‘
[normal]generation,
[normal] conversion or distribution of electric power
[normal]’
[normal] have been 
[normal]used to develop new computer sciences patents in
[normal] 
[normal]‘
[normal]electrical digital data processing
[normal]’
[normal] technologies. Another example is 
[normal]‘
[normal]combustion apparatus using fluent fuel
[normal]’
[normal] technologies
[normal], which
[normal] hav
[normal]e
[normal] spi
[normal]ll
[normal]ed 
[normal]over
[normal] to
[normal] 
[normal]‘
[normal]diagnosis, surgery and
[normal] identification
[normal]’
[normal] 
[normal]patents
[normal] in medical science.
[normal] 
[normal]The Grantham Research Institute is
[normal] currently 
[normal]working on a project that analyses
[normal] the impact of knowledge spillovers from green technologies on business performance.
[normal] This methodology could be applied to UK businesses
[normal],
[normal] in particular to measure the impact of low-carbon innovation on economic growth.
[normal] 
[normal]This project seems 
[normal]very relevant for the work of the LCICG
[normal], and its
[normal] results will be available in Spring/Summer 2014.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.1 
[normal]DECC should 
[normal]prioritises innovation
[normal] 
[normal]funding for
[normal] 
[normal]carbon capture and storage (
[normal]CCS
[normal])
[normal] technologies.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.2 
[normal]Given the current energy mix in the UK, 
[normal]support for 
[normal]CCS
[normal] (including gas, industrial and biomass CCS)
[normal] will be a key component of 
[normal]the Government’s
[normal] 
[normal]strategy for achieving the 
[normal]target
[normal] 
[normal]of
[normal] reduc
[normal]ing
[normal] 
[normal]greenhouse gas
[normal] 
[normal]emissions by 80% 
[normal]by
[normal] 2050
[normal] compared with
[normal] 1990 levels
[normal].
[normal] In addition, CCS technologies are still at an early stage of development
[normal]; when
[normal] 
[normal]G
[normal]ov
[normal]ernment support is most needed.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.3 
[normal]In a recent paper, 
[normal]Dechezleprêtre
[normal] 
[normal]et al
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal](
[normal]2013) 
[normal]f
[normal]ou
[normal]nd that innovations in CCS technologies generate even larger knowledge 
[normal]spillovers
[normal] 
[normal]than renewable energy technologies, implying that the incentives to conduct private research and development activities
[normal], compared to what is socially desirable, are lower
[normal] 
[normal]for CCS
[normal] than 
[normal]for
[normal] 
[normal]other technologies (including 
[normal]renewables
[normal])
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]S
[normal]trong public support is
[normal] 
[normal]therefore
[normal] warranted.
